{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14006"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14006"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.18,0.58,0.06,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111287"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5448"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43460"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111287"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine antenatal care. She is currently nine weeks pregnant with her second child. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications other than a pregnancy multivitamin. She reports she has had all of her childhood immunisations and three COVID-19 vaccinations. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Initial antenatal blood tests are all unremarkable except for low immunity to rubella. During the consultation, she enquires about the recommended vaccinations she should receive during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate combination of vaccinations recommended for this patient during her pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measles-mumps-rubella (MMR), respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) and influenza vaccinations","COVID-19, diphtheria-tetanus-acellular pertussis (dTpa) and influenza vaccinations","Influenza, diphtheria-tetanus-acellular pertussis (dTpa), and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccinations","Diphtheria-tetanus-acellular pertussis (dTpa) and measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccinations","Hepatitis B, influenza and COVID-19 booster vaccinations"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate combination of vaccinations routinely recommended during pregnancy is \u003Cstrong\u003Einfluenza, diphtheria-tetanus-acellular pertussis (dTpa), and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccinations\u003C/strong\u003E. These vaccinations are safe and effective during pregnancy, providing protection for both the mother and the newborn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe influenza vaccine is recommended for all pregnant women at any stage of pregnancy, as pregnant women are at higher risk of severe complications from influenza. The dTpa vaccine is typically given between 20-32 weeks of pregnancy, primarily to protect the newborn against pertussis (whooping cough) in the first few months of life. The RSV vaccine is now recommended for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation to protect newborns from severe RSV disease in their first months of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles-mumps-rubella (MMR)\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is contraindicated during pregnancy as it is a live attenuated vaccine. Live vaccines are generally avoided during pregnancy due to the theoretical risk of harm to the foetus. Despite the patient having low immunity to rubella, she should not receive the MMR vaccine during pregnancy. Instead, she should be vaccinated postpartum, ideally before discharge from the hospital or at her six-week check-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECOVID-19\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is recommended in pregnancy if the patient has not had their primary course. However, it is no longer routinely recommended for all pregnant women to receive a further booster unless they are otherwise eligible, such as if they are immunocompromised. The decision to vaccinate against COVID-19 during pregnancy should be made based on an individual risk-benefit assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is not routinely recommended for all pregnant women. It is only recommended for those at increased risk of hepatitis B infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while these are the general recommendations, individual circumstances may vary. Healthcare providers should always consider the specific needs and risk factors of each pregnant woman when making vaccination recommendations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Influenza and diphtheria-tetanus-acellular pertussis (dTpa) vaccinations are routinely recommended for all pregnant women.","Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccination is now recommended for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation to protect newborns.","Live vaccinations, such as measles-mumps-rubella (MMR), are contraindicated during pregnancy."],"references":["Vaccination for women who are planning pregnancy, pregnant or breastfeeding [Internet]. The Australian Immunisation Handbook. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccination-for-special-risk-groups/vaccination-for-women-who-are-planning-pregnancy-pregnant-or-breastfeeding","Vaccinated pregnant women may consider a further dose during pregnancy [Internet]. The Australian Immunisation Handbook. 2024 [cited 2024 Jul 26]. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/recommendations/vaccinated-pregnant-women-may-consider-a-further-dose-during-pregnancy#:~:text=Unless%20a%20woman%20is%20otherwise"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14006"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T09:50:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T09:50:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6655"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111287"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tag